#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1248
msgid ""
"Click on the opposite side of the strokes: all strokes intersected by the"
" defined line will be affected by the bending."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1250
msgid "Drag in the direction you want to bend strokes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1252
msgid "**To smooth a stroke:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1254
msgid "Select the **Iron** tool (|iron|)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1256
msgid ""
"Click and drag along the stroke you want to smooth. By dragging over and "
"over the stroke will increasingly flatten."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1262
msgid "Joining and Splitting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1263
msgid ""
"To join the ends of two different vector strokes, you can use the "
"**Tape** tool (|tape|). This way it will be possible to handle them as a "
"single stroke, for instance for modifying their bend, or thickness, as a "
"whole."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1631
msgid "tape"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1265
msgid ""
"When the tool is used, the pointer snaps to the closest detected stroke "
"endpoint in order to make the operation easier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1267
msgid ""
"The **Tape** tool (|tape|) can also be used to close gaps along the "
"drawing outline for painting purposes (see :ref:`Closing Gaps in Drawing "
"Outline <closing_gaps_in_drawing_outline>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1269
msgid ""
"To do the contrary, that is to say splitting a stroke in two sections, "
"you can use the **Cutter** tool (|cutter|)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1620
msgid "cutter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1271
msgid "**To join two open ends of one or two strokes:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1273
msgid ""
"Select the **Tape** tool (|tape|), and activate the **Join Vectors** "
"option; activate also the **Smooth** option if you want a smooth joining "
"with no corners."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1277
msgid ""
"Set the type to **Normal** and the mode to **Endpoint to Endpoint**, "
"click a stroke endpoint and drag to a different endpoint; the pointer "
"snaps to the closest detected stroke endpoint."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1279
msgid ""
"Set the type to **Rectangular**, and click and drag to define a box "
"including the endpoints you want to connect; the endpoints will be "
"automatically joined according to the set **Distance** value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1281
msgid ""
"If the strokes you are going to join have different Styles, the Style of "
"the first vector where you click on will be assigned to the second one "
"after joining."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1283
msgid "**To split a stroke:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1285
msgid ""
"Select the **Cutter** tool (|cutter|): the pointer snaps to the closest "
"stroke indicating, with a small highlighted segment, the point where you "
"are going to split the stroke."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1287
msgid "Click to split the stroke at the highlighted point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1293
msgid "Cleaning up Strokes Intersections"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1294
msgid ""
"Vector strokes intersections may be a weak point in drawings to be "
"painted, because if a gap occurs, drawing areas cannot be painted "
"properly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1296
msgid ""
"The best solution for this kind of issue is to overlap the final section "
"of strokes, in order to define clear intersections, then automatically "
"remove the sections that overflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1298
msgid "**To cleanup vector intersections:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1300
msgid ""
"Use the **Selection** tool (|selection|) to select the strokes whose "
"intersections you want to cleanup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1304
msgid "Choose Edit  →  **Remove Vector Overflow**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1306
msgid ""
"Right-click the selection and choose **Remove Vector Overflow** from the "
"menu that opens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1312
msgid "Animation Techniques"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1313
msgid ""
"Besides drawing frame by frame, one image at a time, until you achieve "
"the animation you want, some other techniques are easier to achieve "
"thanks to Tahoma2D features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1315
msgid ""
"Whatever the technique is, you can control your work and how smooth the "
"animation is by using the onion skin, that allows you to view more than "
"one image in the viewer at the same time as reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1321
msgid "Modelling a Vector Drawing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1322
msgid ""
"Instead of animating a level by starting every time from a blank frame, "
"you can duplicate a vector drawing and make subsequent modifications. You"
" can do it even if the drawings are painted, because the styles used to "
"paint will automatically follow the shape of the areas you modify (see  "
":ref:`Editing Drawings <editing_drawings>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1324
msgid ""
"The sequence of the animation level drawings can be easily controlled in "
"the Level Strip."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1326
msgid ""
"You can use both the Cells  →  **Duplicate Drawing** command and the "
"standard **Copy** and **Paste** commands to make a copy of a drawing that"
" you can later modify to create slight movements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1328
msgid ""
"When you use the **Duplicate Drawing** command, the selected drawing is "
"duplicated in the following frame. If the following frame already "
"contains a drawing, it's shifted down in order to insert the duplicated "
"drawing in the sequence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1330
msgid ""
"When you use the **Copy** and **Paste** commands, you can also decide the"
" frame of the Level Strip where you want to paste the drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1332
msgid ""
"Once finished, you can make a copy of the modified drawing, and modify it"
" in its turn. You can go on duplicating and modifying drawings until you "
"complete the animation level."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1334
msgid "**To create an animation level by modelling vector drawings:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1336
msgid ""
"In the Viewer, select a drawing of the vector animation level you want to"
" edit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1338
msgid "In the Level Strip, select the drawing you want to duplicate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1340
msgid ""
"Copy the selected drawing in the following frame by doing one of the "
"following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1342
msgid "Choose Cells  →  **Duplicate Drawing**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1344
msgid ""
"Choose Edit  →  **Copy**, then select the following frame and choose "
"**Paste**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1346
msgid "Select the new drawing in the Level Strip."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1348
msgid "Use modifier tools to modify the drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1350
msgid ""
"Go on duplicating and modifying drawings until you complete the animation"
" level."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1356
msgid "Using the In-betweener with Vector Drawings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1357
msgid ""
"An animation technique reserved to vector animation levels is the use of "
"the **Inbetween** command. Inbetween creates in-between drawings from the"
" two extremes of a range of selected frames in the Level Strip."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1359
msgid ""
"When more than two frames are selected in the Level Strip, a vertical "
"strip labeled **INBETWEEN** is displayed on the right of each frame. By "
"clicking on it, all frames between the first and the last selected, will "
"be overwritten by images interpolating from the first to the last "
"drawings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1363
msgid ""
"Duplicate a drawing; modify it; insert blank frames; select the frame "
"range, then click the INBETWEEN vertical bar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1365
msgid ""
"The interpolated drawings are created by taking into account the number "
"of the strokes, and the strokes' direction. This means that the result "
"will depend on the way drawings were made. For example if the first image"
" is a single shape drawn clockwise, and the last is another shape, you "
"will get different results depending on the way it was drawn, clockwise "
"or counterclockwise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1367
msgid ""
"To obtain the best results with complex drawings, copy the drawing you "
"want to interpolate from, and paste it in another frame of the level "
"strip. Modify the pasted drawing without adding and deleting strokes, but"
" only distorting and moving existing strokes (see  :ref:`Editing Drawings"
" <editing_drawings>`  ). Select the whole range and then perform the "
"interpolation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1369
msgid ""
"The interpolation acceleration can be controlled in the dialog that opens"
" prior to performing in-betweening. Options are the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1371
msgid "**Linear**, for a constant interpolation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1373
msgid "**Ease In**, for an interpolation starting slowly, then getting faster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1375
msgid "**Ease Out**, for an interpolation starting quickly, then getting slower."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1377
msgid ""
"**Ease In / Ease Out**, for an interpolation starting slowly, getting "
"faster, then getting slower again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1379
msgid ""
"If you want the interpolation to happen slower or faster, you can insert "
"frames, or cut them, and use the in-betweener again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1381
msgid "**To create in-between drawings:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1383
msgid "Select the level where you want to perform interpolation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1385
msgid ""
"In the Level Strip select the frame range, from the drawing you want to "
"interpolate from, to the one you want to interpolate to. If you want the "
"interpolation to last more frames, make room for more drawings with the "
"Edit  →  **Insert** command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1387
msgid ""
"Click the vertical strip labeled **INBETWEEN** displayed on the right of "
"the frame range selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1389
msgid ""
"Select the **Interpolation:** mode among **Linear**, **Ease In**, **Ease "
"Out**, **Ease In / Esase Out**, and click the **Inbetween** button."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1391
msgid "**To optimize the in-betweening process:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1393
msgid "Create and paint the drawing you want to interpolate from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1397
msgid ""
"**Copy** and **Paste** it in another frame of the Level Strip, "
"considering the number of in-between drawings you want to achieve."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1399
msgid ""
"**Duplicate** it and insert as many empty frames as the number of in-"
"between drawings you want to achieve."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1401
msgid ""
"Modify the pasted or duplicated drawing using the modifier tools, to "
"create the final drawing of the interpolation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1403
msgid ""
"Select the frame range from the drawing you want to interpolate from, to "
"the one you want to interpolate to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1405
msgid ""
"Click the vertical **INBETWEEN** strip displayed on the right of the "
"frame range selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1411
msgid "Rotoscoping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1412
msgid "Rotoscoping consists of tracing drawings taking a live clip as reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1416
msgid "Using the rotoscoping technique to trace the movement of a hand."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1418
msgid ""
"As you can import clips and image sequences in a scene, you can simply "
"load them, and create an animation level by drawing in the Viewer, while "
"the frames of the clips are visible underneath. See  :ref:`Using the File"
" Browser <using_the_file_browser>`  ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1420
msgid ""
"The way to obtain best results is not trying to reproduce with fidelity "
"the clip, but to use its frames just as a reference to better understand "
"the movement or the transformation of the clip’s subject. In this way you"
" can take advantage, for example, of a natural movement represented in "
"the clip, without renouncing an expressive drawing style."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1422
msgid "**To perform rotoscoping:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1424
msgid ""
"Load a video clip or image sequence in an Xsheet column (or Timeline "
"layer)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1426
msgid ""
"In the Xsheet/Timeline select a cell in a column on the right of the "
"column (or in a layer on top of the layer) containing the clip you "
"loaded. The image of the clip placed at the same frame of the cell you "
"selected will be visible in the Viewer while you're drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1428
msgid ""
"Create a new animation level and use tools to trace the first drawing in "
"the Viewer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1430
msgid "Move to subsequent frames, and trace the next drawings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1436
msgid "Cloning Levels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1437
msgid ""
"Sometimes it may be useful to create a clone of a level, or a part of it,"
" in order to edit it without affecting the original one. For example you "
"may want to create a new animation level starting from the drawings of "
"another level, in order to have two sequences similar but not identical."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1439
msgid ""
"The **Clone** command allows you to create a copy of the selected cells, "
"preserving the numbering order and assigning a new name to it. The "
"**_clone** suffix appended to the name of the level is the default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1441
msgid ""
"The cloned level will contain *only drawings exposed in the selected "
"cells*, even if the original level is composed of more drawings; they "
"will be automatically exposed in the column on the right (or layer on "
"top) of the selection, shifting the following columns/layers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1443
msgid ""
"The new level will be available in the Scene Cast as a new element; it "
"will be saved in the **+drawings** or **+extras** default folder, "
"according to the format of the original file, as soon as you save it with"
" the **Save Level** command, or you save the scene."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1445
msgid ""
"The cell selection can also spread over several columns/layers: in this "
"case the same number of new columns/layers will be inserted to make room "
"for the cloning result. If more than one level is selected, the same "
"number of new levels will be created and it's not possible to assign a "
"name to the cloned levels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1447
msgid "**To clone levels:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1449
msgid "Select the cells you want to clone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1453
msgid "Choose Cells  →  **Clone**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1455
msgid ""
"Right-click in the selection and choose **Clone** from the menu that "
"opens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1457
msgid "Enter a **Level Name:** and press **OK** to confirm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1463
msgid "Using Onion Skin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1464
msgid ""
"If you want to view more than one level drawing at the same time in the "
"Viewer as reference when you create drawings, or you want to check the "
"animation, you can activate the Onion Skin mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1466
msgid ""
"The Onion Skin is available both in the Xsheet/Timeline and in the Level "
"Strip, according to where the cursor showing the current frame is "
"displayed, as the onion skin can be activated starting from the cursor "
"and managed in the frame number column/bar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1470
msgid ""
"A column animation displayed with the relative Onion Skin set for 6 "
"previous frames, step two, and an absolute Onion Skin set at frame 35."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1472
msgid ""
"When a frame of the Level Strip is selected, the onion skin applies to "
"the *current level* only, referring to the sequence of the full animation"
" level as it was created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1474
msgid ""
"When a cell of the Xsheet/Timeline is selected, the onion skin applies to"
" the current level, according to how the drawing sequence is exposed in "
"the scene, including movements and transformations performed thanks to "
"the object animation (see  :ref:`Animating Objects <animating_objects>`  "
"), while the rest of the scene in the current frame will be visible as "
"usual. If you want, you can also extend the onion skin to the whole "
"content of the Xsheet/Timeline, to allow references to all of the "
"animated or moving elements in the scene as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1476
msgid ""
"The *relative* Onion Skin mode displays frames in relation to the "
"position of the current frame. For instance you can activate the frame "
"previous to the current one, and every time you change the current frame,"
" the previous frame will be displayed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1478
msgid ""
"The *fixed* Onion Skin mode displays the selected frame independently "
"from the current frame. For instance you can activate frame 5, and every "
"time you change the current frame, frame 5 will be displayed in Onion "
"Skin mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1480
msgid ""
"The way images are displayed in Onion Skin mode can be customized in the "
"Preferences pane. It's possible to define the **Paper Thickness**, to set"
" an independent color correction for previous and following frames, and "
"to **Display Lines Only** for Vector and Smart Raster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1482
msgid "**To activate or deactivate frames in Relative Onion Skin mode:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1486
msgid ""
"In the Xsheet, click the small romboid markers available to the left of "
"the frames column (or above the frame bar in the Timeline). Click and "
"drag automatically activates or deactivates a series of frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1488
msgid ""
"In the Level Strip, click the small circular markers available to the "
"left of the strip frames. Click and drag automatically activates or "
"deactivates a series of frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1490
msgid "**To activate or deactivate frames in Fixed Onion Skin mode:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1494
msgid ""
"In the Xsheet, click the small ghosted romboid markers available to the "
"very left of the frames column (or above the frame bar in the Timeline). "
"Click and drag automatically activates or deactivates a series of frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1496
msgid ""
"In the Level Strip, click the small ghosted circular markers available to"
" the very left of the strip frames. Click and drag automatically "
"activates or deactivates a series of frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1498
msgid "**To Deactivate (or Activate again) the Onion Skin mode:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1502
msgid ""
"Double-click over the big circle to the left of the current frame cursor."
" Double-click again to activate it back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1504
msgid ""
"Right-click in the Viewer or in the frames column/bar of the "
"Xsheet/Timeline, and choose **Deactivate Onion Skin** or **Activate Onion"
" Skin** in the menu that opens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1506
msgid ""
"The first time you activate Onion Skin mode by Right-clicking in the "
"Viewer or the Xsheet/Timeline frames column/bar, a default relative onion"
" skin mode activates, showing the previous three frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1508
msgid "**To Extend the onion skin to the Whole Scene Content:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1510
msgid "Activate the onion skin in the Xsheet/Timeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1512
msgid ""
"Right-click in the Viewer or in the frame column/bar of the "
"Xsheet/Timeline, and choose **Extend Onion Skin to Scene** from the menu "
"that opens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1514
msgid "**To Limit the onion skin to the Current Level:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1516
msgid ""
"Right-click in the Viewer or in the frame column/bar of the "
"Xsheet/Timeline, and choose **Limit Onion Skin to Level** from the menu "
"that opens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1518
msgid "**To customize the way images are displayed in onion skin mode:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1520
msgid "Choose File  →  Preferences  →  **Onion Skin**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1524
msgid ""
"Set a value for the **Paper Thickness** parameter; the lower the value, "
"the more transparent the drawings displayed in Onion Skin mode will be."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1526
msgid ""
"Use the **Previous Frames Correction** to set a color for displaying "
"previous frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1528
msgid ""
"Use the **Following Frames Correction** to set a color for displaying "
"following frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1530
msgid ""
"Activate the **Display Lines Only** option to display Vector or Smart "
"Raster levels with lines only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1536
msgid "Using Shift and Trace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1537
msgid ""
"The **Shift and Trace** function can help you in the creation of animated"
" levels as if you were drawing on paper using a light table; in fact it "
"allows you to use the previous and next key drawings as references, while"
" you insert an inbetween or a break down."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1539
msgid ""
"It's possible to temporary move and rotate the drawings you want to use "
"as reference, to fit the position where you want to draw the inbetween. "
"It's also possible to automatically set the position of the reference "
"drawings creating and editing a path of action line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1541
msgid ""
"To better check the new drawing and the animation, you can toggle the "
"Shift and Trace visualization on or off the Viewer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1543
msgid "**To enter the Shift and Trace view:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1545
msgid ""
"Position the frame cursor on the frame where you want to draw the "
"inbetween drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1547
msgid ""
"Enable View  →  **Shift and Trace**; the previous and next drawings will "
"be visualized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1549
msgid "**To Edit the Position of the reference drawings:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1551
#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1571
msgid ""
"Position the frame cursor where you want to draw the inbetween drawing "
"and sketch the path of action line beteween your reference points."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1553
#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1573
msgid "Activate View  →  **Edit Shift**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1555
msgid ""
"Click on the drawing you want to reposition in the Viewer, or use the "
"**Previous Drawing** / **Following Drawing** options in the tool options "
"bar; the related reference drawing bounding box will be displayed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1559
msgid ""
"Click and drag *inside the bounding box* to **move** the reference "
"drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1561
msgid ""
"Click and drag *outside the bounding box* to **rotate** the reference "
"drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1563
msgid "Click and drag *the center handle* to change the **center of rotation**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1565
msgid ""
"Click and drag *any corner handle of the bounding box* to **scale** the "
"reference drawing from its center."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1567
msgid "Repeat the same steps on the second reference drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:1569
msgid "**To automatically Edit the Position of the reference drawings:**"
msgstr ""

